<!-- EXTENDED BIO -->
<div class="about-full">
  <div class="about-full-intro">
    <p>Jay Trainer is a songwriter from Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, whose music lives at the intersection of folk, acoustic rock, and something harder to name — the sound of a place, a season, a memory that won't quite let go.</p>
    <p>With eight releases spanning nearly two decades, the catalogue tells a story of quiet persistence. From the raw, unpolished live recordings of *The Waking Hours* (2006) to the expansive, firelight-recorded *A Whisper of Ruin — Deluxe Edition* (2019), each album marks a chapter in a life lived through music.</p>
    <p>The work has never chased trends. It has grown like the old trees that show up again and again in the lyrics — slowly, deliberately, shaped by the particular soil of western Pennsylvania. Songs about loss and rootedness. About what it costs to leave and what it means to stay. About the deep-seated instinct that tells you, before you can even name it, that this is what you were made to do.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- TIMELINE -->
  <div class="about-timeline">
    <h3>The <em>Timeline</em></h3>
    <div class="timeline-item">
      <div class="timeline-year">2006</div>
      <div class="timeline-text"><strong>The Waking Hours</strong> — The first recordings. Nine tracks of studio work and raw live cuts from Pittsburgh venues. Where it all began.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline-item">
      <div class="timeline-year">2010</div>
      <div class="timeline-text"><strong>Of The Sun</strong> — Ten tracks of expansive, folk-rooted songwriting. The album where the sound matured and the ambition widened. Home of *Better To Breathe* and *Fractured*.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline-item">
      <div class="timeline-year">2015</div>
      <div class="timeline-text"><strong>Den Of Thieves</strong> — Six tracks of confident, stride-hitting songwriting. Originals, reworked classics, and a seven-minute live epic.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline-item">
      <div class="timeline-year">2019</div>
      <div class="timeline-text"><strong>A Whisper Of Ruin — Deluxe Edition</strong> — The magnum opus. Fifteen tracks shaped by loss and beauty, expanded with live cuts, acoustic reworkings, and three new chapters.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline-item">
      <div class="timeline-year">2021</div>
      <div class="timeline-text"><strong>Blackout Asylum (Remastered)</strong> — Five tracks stripped to the bone and rebuilt with new clarity. Songs about clearing out and starting over.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline-item">
      <div class="timeline-year">2023</div>
      <div class="timeline-text"><strong>The Southern Winds / Last Days Of Summer / Lifeline</strong> — Three singles exploring new territory: a remix, a band recording, and a stripped-back cover.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

